ound and parallel influence both on science and our perception of natural world today. In a lively comparison, Michael J. Lannoo shows how deeply these two ecological luminaries influenced the emergence both of environmentalism and conservation biology. In particular, he looks closely at how they each derived their ideas about the possible future of humanity based on their understanding of natural communities. Leopold and Ricketts both believed that humans cannot place themselves above earth's ecosystems and continue to survive. In light of climate change, invasive species, and collapsing ecosystems, their most important shared idea emerges as a powerful key to the future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aEcologyzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aEnvironmentalismzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aNatural historyzUnited StatesxHistory. 7aNATURE / Environmental Conservation & Protection.2bisacsh  a20th century.  aaldo leopold.  abiography.  aclimate change.  acollapsing ecosystems.  aconservation biology.  adiscussion books.  aeasy to read.  aecologists.  aecology.  aecosystems.  aed ricketts.  aenvironmentalism.  afamous scientists.  ahistorical scientists.  ahistory of environmentalism.  ainvasive species.  anatural communities.  anatural science.  anatural world.  anaturalism.  anonfiction.  arelated work.  aretrospective.  ascience majors.  ascience.  ascientists.  astudents and teachers.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052026478640uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094606440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520946064423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520946064/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Packag